{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:36:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17623"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17623"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.6,0.1,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10337"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57174"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7755"},{"type":"tags","id":"7804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA randomised controlled trial investigating a new probiotic yogurt finds a statistically significant increase in gut microbiome diversity compared to regular yogurt (p = 0.03). The mean difference between groups is a 1% increase in bacterial species diversity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the clinical relevance of these results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Statistical significance proves clinical benefit","Small effect size with uncertain clinical relevance","Results demonstrate strong treatment effect","Results are not statistically valid","No conclusions possible without p\u003C0.01"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDespite statistical significance, the \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall effect size with uncertain clinical relevance\u003C/strong\u003E best describes these results. A 1% difference in bacterial diversity, while statistically significant, may be too small to produce meaningful clinical benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect interpretations are common misconceptions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStatistical significance proves clinical benefit\u003C/strong\u003E - Statistical significance (p\u0026lt;0.05) does not automatically indicate meaningful clinical benefits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResults demonstrate strong treatment effect\u003C/strong\u003E - A 1% difference represents a very small effect size regardless of statistical significance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResults are not statistically valid\u003C/strong\u003E - The p-value of 0.03 meets conventional criteria for statistical significance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo conclusions possible without p\u0026lt;0.01\u003C/strong\u003E - While p\u0026lt;0.01 is a stricter threshold, p\u0026lt;0.05 is widely accepted as statistically significant\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis example demonstrates how statistically significant results (p\u0026lt;0.05) may not translate to meaningful clinical benefits. Both statistical significance and effect size should be considered when evaluating research findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Statistical significance (p\u003C0.05) does not equate to clinical importance or meaningful treatment effects.","Small effect sizes can be statistically significant but clinically irrelevant.","Research findings should be evaluated based on both statistical significance and clinical meaningfulness."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57174"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17623"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57174"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T10:57:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T10:59:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10337"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c